hey connect, and of course <tt>fail2ban</tt> stops <i>repeated</i> attacks, but what if bad IPs could be blocked <b>before</b> they connect?</p>\n<p>By working collaboratively - sharing attack data - <i>WP fail2ban Blocklist</i> does exactly that.</p>\n<h3>How</h3>\n<p>The Blocklist Network Service (BNS) collects attack data from participating sites, performs some analytical magic, and sends back a list of IPs that are attacking sites now but haven\'t yet attacked that site.</p>\n<p>In other words, each site regularly gets a unique list of IPs to block <b>preemptively</b>.</p>\n<h3>GDPR</h3>\n<p>The BNS doesn\'t collect personal data, and bots don\'t have rights.</p>\n<p>That said, the BNS only collects the minimum data required (time, IP, event), and only for IPs that have behaved maliciously.</p>\n<p>Of course, it is possible that some data is generated by <i>people</i> behaving maliciously, but the BNS has no way to differentiate - and nor should it: an attack is an attack.</p>\";s:17:\"short_description\";s:58:\"A <b>preemptive collaborative blocklist</b> for WordPress.\";s:10:\"banner_url\";s:67:\"https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/freemius/plugins/6750/banner.png\";s:15:\"card_banner_url\";s:72:\"https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/freemius/plugins/6750/card_banner.png\";s:15:\"selling_point_0\";s:0:\"\";s:15:\"selling_point_1\";s:0:\"\";s:15:\"selling_point_2\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"screenshots\";N;s:2:\"id\";s:4:\"1811\";s:7:\"created\";s:19:\"2020-09-17 00:17:38\";s:7:\"updated\";s:19:\"2021-06-19 07:49:45\";}s:12:\"premium_slug\";s:27:\"wp-fail2ban-addon-blocklist\";}}}s:7:\"created\";i:1701109593;s:9:\"timestamp\";i:1701195993;}s:53:\"get:/v1/plugins/3072/addons/pricing.json?type=visible\";O:8:\"stdClass\":3:{s:6:\"result\";O:8:\"stdClass\":1:{s:6:\"addons\";a:3:{i:0;O:8:\"stdClass\":2:{s:2:\"id\";i:3564;s:5:\"plans\";a:1:{i:0;O:8:\"stdClass\":22:{s:9:\"plugin_id\";s:4:\"3564\";s:4:\"name\";s:4:\"free\";s:5:\"title\";s:4:\"Free\";s:11:\"description\";N;s:17:\"is